<article class="blog--container blog-preview">
<h2 class="blog--title">
<a href="/blog/2015/05/19/this-week-in-spring-may-19th-2015"> This Week in Spring - May 19th, 2015</a>
</h2>
<header class="meta-data--container">
<div class="meta-data--item desktop-only">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon engineering"></div>
<a class="category" href="/blog/category/engineering">Engineering</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<img class="meta-data--icon" src="https://gravatar.com/avatar/fb22593caf24e4bb4c98d467cdd247e6?s=20&amp;d=mm" />
<a class="author" href="/team/jlong">Josh Long</a>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon calendar"></div>
<time class="date" pubdate="" datetime="2015-05-19 23:02:00.0">May 19, 2015</time>
</div>
<div class="meta-data--item">
<div class="meta-data--icon icon blog-icon comments"></div>
<a class="comments" data-disqus-identifier="2127" href="/blog/2015/05/19/this-week-in-spring-may-19th-2015#disqus_thread">
</a></div>
</header>
<section class="blog--post desktop-only">
<div><p>Welcome to another installment of <em>This Week in Spring</em>! As usual, we’ve got a<br>lot to cover this week so let’s get to it!</p>
<ul>
<li>the good Dr. Dave Syer is back it again with this seventh installment on how to better modularize the Angular.js client that talks to a <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/13/modularizing-the-client-angular-js-and-spring-security-part-vii">backend Spring Security, Spring Boot, and Spring Security OAuth-powered service</a> and with this eighth installment which looks <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/19/testing-an-angular-application-angular-js-and-spring-security-part-viii">at how to test that Angular.js application</a>!</li>
<li>Spring Security lead and all around amazing, test-driven dude, Rob Winch just <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/14/spring-test-htmlunit-1-0-0-rc1-released">announced Spring Test HtmlUnit 1.0.0.RC1</a> with a lot of new polish.</li>
<li>Spring Batch lead Michael Minella <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/19/spring-batch-3-0-4-release-is-now-available">just announced that Spring Batch 3.0.4, a maintenance release, is now available</a></li>
<li>Spring Social lead Craig Walls just announced that two maintenance releases, <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/19/spring-social-1-1-2-released">Spring Social 1.1.2</a> and <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/15/spring-social-1-1-1-released">Spring Social 1.1.1</a>, have been released</li>
<li>On May 28th, join Pivotal’s own Greg Turnquist: <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/05/webinar-debug-and-maintain-your-spring-boot-app">How to Debug and Maintain your Spring Boot App</a></li>
<li>Turkcell’s Erdem Gunay, and our pal, is giving a webinar on June 9th explaining <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/06/webinar-a-comprehensive-spring-showcase-personal-cloud-storage-application">how Spring is pretty comprehensively used in Turkcell’s personal cloud service</a>.</li>
<li>longtime Spring community member <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/30288959/eureka-peers-not-synchronized">David Welch had a question about setting up a highly available Netflix Eureka installation</a> and Spring Cloud co-founder Spencer Gibb helped him along on this super useful StackOverflow.com post.</li>
<li>Fancy using JUnit <code>@Rule</code> instances instead of being forced to specify Spring’s JUnit <code>TestRunner</code> (which effectively removes the ability to use <em>other</em> sometimes required <code>TestRunner</code> implementations)? Check out the <a href="https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-framework/commit/d1b1c4f888b5ab5c60cf4beb87f577143bdbebe7">upcoming Spring framework 4.2 support already in master</a>!</li>
<li>on May 27th the Seattle Continuous Delivery Meetup <a href="https://www.meetup.com/seattle-continuous-delivery/events/222464656/">is having a Spring Boot talk</a>! Naturally. Check it out. Spring Boot fits well in a continuous delivery pipeline: it’s easy to build isolated, testable, and production-ready applications.</li>
<li>Yet another (well done, by the way!) post on how to <a href="https://www.jiwhiz.com/blogs/Spring_Boot_Docker_MySQL_Demo">setup Spring Boot applications and containerize them with Docker</a>. Seems this is a popular topic! <a href="https://spring.io/guides/gs/spring-boot-docker/">Good thing we have a guide</a>!</li>
<li>Spring and Groovy Tool Suite ninja <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/11/new-in-sts-3-7-0-spring-boot-yaml-editor">Kris De Volder announced the STS support for YAML</a> last week - have you tried it yet?</li>
<li>the <em>IS Applications Development Services</em> blog has a nice post on <a href="http://www.appsdev.is.ed.ac.uk/blog/?p=501">documenting Spring Boot applications with Swagger</a>. I like Swagger, but I’d recommend also trying out <a href="https://github.com/spring-projects/spring-restdocs">Spring REST Docs</a> which are less invasive - they live in the unit-tests - <em>and</em> they’re Asciidoctor-friendly.</li>
<li>Wow, were are finally out of SpringOne2GX replays! This is the last batch, mostly Groovy and Grails. First, Baruch Sadogursky from JFrog talks about <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/19/springone2gx-2014-replay-grails-plugin-testing-strategies">Grails Plugin Testing Strategies</a>. Then David Dawson, from Simplicity Itself talks about <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/19/springone2gx-2014-replay-philosophical-architecture-in-grails">Philosophical Architecture in Grails</a>. Also, Ken Kousen <a href="https://spring.io/blog/2015/05/19/springone2gx-2014-replay-groovy-vampires-combining-groovy-rest-nosql-and-more">Groovy Vampires: Combining Groovy, REST, NoSQL, and more</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</section>
<a class="blog-preview--readmore desktop-only" href="/blog/2015/05/19/this-week-in-spring-may-19th-2015">
Read more...
</a>
</article>
